[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering test placement and coverage**\n\nI’m thinking about whether to move a test into the package org_objenesis instead of COM, but I need to provide COM.jrockit.MemberAccess as it requires the COM package. It looks okay for the test to be outside the library package and located in a dedicated test file under src/test/java.\n\nThe MethodHandle doesn't appear due to a note about avoiding reflection unless necessary, and I suspect the workflow instrumentation may have missed some aspects. I need to figure out why coverage indicates that certain class fields aren't covered.\n\n**Investigating class$ behavior and coverage**\n\nI'm realizing the source doesn't actually contain class$ because of how the decompiler works. Line 41 in the report points to that. The class$ method is synthetic and created by the compiler, which might limit how dynamic tracker calls it. \n\nIf the helper executes during image building, it may not track runtime correctly, which could explain the false report. There’s also a question of whether invoking `Class.forName` is overridden in a native context. I wonder if we can use a public API to trigger a NoClassDefFoundError without directly calling class$.\n\n**Considering helper placement for testing**\n\nI'm wondering if I can place a non-test helper in the same package under src/test/java to access package-private methods. The guidelines say to keep tests outside the library’s packages, but maybe a helper isn't really a test? \n\nHowever, the focus is on having a dedicated Java test file. It seems I can't include package org.objenesis in the same file because it's under the COM package. Should I add a second file instead? That might be the best way to go.\n\n**Inspecting task progress**\n\nI see that the latest successful coverage didn’t include everything it should have. I think it’s important to inspect the logs after the second a