kupIn` to set static synthetic fields to null and then call the public constructor instead of direct reflection, since that might be a better approach. This is related to the JVM access API, so I should ensure the `class$` is invoked via bytecode, not through the method handle. My plan is to replace the method handle with a test that resets the synthetic fields and then instantiates the object. I might need to re-run `getDeclaredMethod` afterward too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering method metadata**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether existing class method metadata is really necessary. If I decide to remove direct calls to the method, then maybe I don’t need to reflect on the class metadata anymore. Also, VarHandle can access private fields through MethodHandles, which might be an analysis that’s already known, but I’m not sure if the constant names need that metadata. Let's explore this further to clarify.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Editing commit status**\\n\\nI think we can create a new commit that alters the current state. That's good! It seems like I just need to gather the status, focusing on any untracked metadata. Once I have that, I can proceed to edit. This part is crucial to ensure everything is updated correctly before proceeding. I'm looking forward to finalizing this and making sure everything reflects the changes properly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_xXZCF6y5SwoyFdrEZPh4YtO7|fc_02f61b83073783bd0169ef71b066f4819098f1b8c9d6cb9a1d", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.objenesis/objenesis/1.2/src/test/java/COM/jrockit/reflect/JRockit131InstantiatorTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandle;\nimport java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;\nimport java.lang.invoke.MethodType;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Constructor;\n\nimport org.assertj.core.api.Assertions;", "newText": "import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;\nimport java.lang.invoke.VarHandle;\nimport java.lang.reflect.Co